{"id":"2001.03208","submitter":"Jos\\'e L. Cereceda","authors":"Jos\\'e L. Cereceda","title":"Figurate numbers and sums of powers of integers","comments":"15 pages, improved presentation","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recently, Marko and Litvinov (ML) conjectured that, for all positive integers\n$n$ and $p$, the $p$-th power of $n$ admits the representation $n^p =\n\\sum_{\\ell =0}^{p-1} (-1)^{l} c_{p,\\ell} F_{n}^{p-\\ell}$, where\n$F_{n}^{p-\\ell}$ is the $n$-th hyper-tetrahedron number of dimension $p-\\ell$\nand $c_{p,\\ell}$ denotes the number of $(p -\\ell)$-dimensional facets formed by\ncutting the $p$-dimensional cube $0 \\leq x_1, x_2, \\ldots, x_p \\leq n-1$. In\nthis paper we show that the ML conjecture is true for every natural number $p$.\nOur proof relies on the fact that the validity of the ML conjecture necessarily\nimplies that $c_{p,\\ell} = (p-\\ell)! S(p, p-\\ell)$, where $S(p,p-\\ell)$ are the\nStirling numbers of the second kind. Furthermore, we provide a number of\nequivalent formulas expressing the sum of powers $\\sum_{i=1}^{n} i^p$ as a\nlinear combination of figurate numbers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 9 Jan 2020 20:08:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 16 Jan 2020 16:14:45 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 30 Jan 2020 17:27:16 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 18 Feb 2020 16:57:04 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Sun, 18 Apr 2021 15:27:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-04-20"}
